      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe ~9 log-unit advantage of EDTA over NTA for Fe³⁺ is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**: EDTA wraps around Fe³⁺ with six donor atoms (4 carboxylates + 2 amines) versus NTA's four (3 carboxylates + 1 amine). The large positive ΔS values for both complexes confirm that complex formation is **entropy-driven**, as expected when multiple water molecules are released from the metal's coordination sphere. Notably, the Fe³⁺–EDTA complex (log K = 25.1) is one of the strongest metal–EDTA complexes known, which is why EDTA is widely used as an iron chelator in medicine, agriculture, and water treatment.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Standard Reference Database 46 — Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
